                  <decoDesc>
                    <summary>Miniatures, all in twentieth-century hand</summary>
                    <decoNote type="miniature" xml:id="d01">
                        <locus target="#ir #iir"/>
                        <desc>Crude drawings of faces and figures</desc>
                     </decoNote>
                    <decoNote type="miniature" xml:id="d02">
                        <locus target="#iiv(erso)"/>
                        <desc>Saint standing with arms upraised <ref type="authFile" corresp="AT1035HolyMan"/>
                        </desc>
                        <note>The style of artwork and the pose is reminiscent of the ground hornbill painter’s work as seen in
                        Bodleian MS. Aeth. e. 28, f. 1v (see Demeke and Delamarter, Plate 9, p. 148). A piece of cloth is sewn to the top of the folio to
                        provide cover for the miniature</note>
                      </decoNote>
                    <decoNote type="miniature" xml:id="d03">
                        <locus target="#137v"/>
                        <desc>An Evangelist, copying a gospel <ref type="authFile" corresp="AT1013EvaPortrait"/>
                        </desc>
                     </decoNote>
                    <decoNote type="frame" xml:id="d04">
                      Decorative designs: <locus target="#1v #7r #14v #22v #32r #39r #44v #53r #59r #63v #71r #76r #88v #98v #101v #106v #112r #124v"/> (<foreign xml:lang="gez">ሐረግ፡</foreign> in red and black and brown ink);
                      <locus target="#136r #140r #141v #143v #144v"/>, (alternating red and black dots).
                    </decoNote>
                  </decoDesc>
                  <additions>
                    <list>
                        <item xml:id="a1">
                           <desc>
                              <locus target="#ir"/> pen trial</desc>
                        </item>
                        <item xml:id="a2">
                           <desc>
                              <locus target="#iv"/>", in faint purple ink: List of names</desc>
                        </item>
                        <item xml:id="a3">
                           <desc>
                              <locus target="#145v"/> scrawls</desc>
                        </item>
                        <item xml:id="a4">
                           <desc>
                              <locus target="#59r"/>
                        Several devices mark the midpoint of the psalms:
                        1) the letters of the words of the line are written in alternating red and black ink;
                        2) A symbol inside a box with the word, <foreign xml:lang="gez">መንፈቅ፡</foreign>;
                        and 3) the word <foreign xml:lang="gez">ዝየ፡</foreign> apparently added after the other indications</desc>
                        </item>
                        <item xml:id="a5">
                           <desc>
                          Scribal intervention: words of text are written interlinearly (<locus target="#11v #21v #33r #34v #62r"/>, etc.);
                          and lines of text are written interlinearly (<locus target="#13v #18v #57r #106v"/>, etc.);
                          and in the fore edge margin with a symbol (+) marking the location where the text is to be inserted (<locus target="#59r"/>, line 9; <locus target="#63r"/>, line 13),
                          and in another case where the symbol (+) is used interlinearly to point to a text written interlinearly (<locus target="#121r"/>, line 14);
                          erasure markings are visible (<locus target="#138v #140v #141v"/>, etc.);
                          text has been removed (<locus target="#29v #39v #53r"/>, etc.)
                        </desc>
                        </item>
                        <item xml:id="a6">
                           <desc>
                          This scribe has avoided the problem of lines of text too long to fit on one line by adopting an aspect ratio that leaves ample room
                          for the width of most lines. On a few occasions, the line would have been too long and the scribe finishes the end of the line with
                          words written smaller so as to avoid leftover text (e.g., <locus target="#7v #9r #9v #22r #22v"/>).  Occasionally a line is still too long and has to be
                          completed above or below the end of the line (e.g., <locus target="#1r #2v #22r #27r"/>)
                        </desc>
                        </item>
                    </list>
                  </additions>
